Continuing this string and dialog.  I met a man while in counseling who had never set foot in vietnam. This man was in worse shape than half the guys in my group.<br>
  It seems that this man grew up in a small town and his entire high school graduating class enlisted into the army.  They all went to basic and ait together.  They all tried to get assignments together but he was the only one who got posted to Germany.  His entire class was assigned to various places in Nam.  Today he is the only survivor of that high school class.  <br>
That is why I personally have tolerance for those who weren't in country but survived viet nam.  <br>
So when someone sees my bumber sticker that says &quot;University of South VietNam;  College of Warfare&quot;  and gives me a wave or thumbs up,  I always acknowledge it.  <br>
Someone told me once that for every grunt in the bush , it took seven support people to feed, clothe, pay, arm, that one grunt.  So when someone asks &quot;What did you do in country?&quot;  DON&quot;T discount your service or your job.  The biggest part of my recovery was accepting the fact that what I did was important and that I did the BEST JOB that I could do for a seventeen year old BOY!!<br>
This is an opening to anyone to talk and heal.  And feel good about what they did in country.  <br>
Remember  they we winning when we left!
